      \field{abstract}{The exponential growth of healthcare data from electronic health records (EHRs), clinical registries, and administrative databases presents unprecedented opportunities for research and clinical decision support. However, these real-world data sources are plagued by quality issues including missing values, outliers, semantic inconsistencies, and formatting errors that compromise their utility for secondary analysis. This study presents a scalable, hybrid framework for automated data quality assessment and cleaning that integrates rule-driven validation with Python-based machine learning techniques. The framework combines three complementary approaches: (1) rule-based validation using configurable domain knowledge and FHIR-compliant data standards, (2) unsupervised machine learning algorithms (Isolation Forest, DBSCAN, and KNN) for outlier detection, and (3) advanced imputation methods (MissForest, iterative imputation) for missing data handling. The framework was evaluated using two large-scale healthcare datasets comprising 1.2 million patient records from multiple clinical sites. The proposed framework achieved 94.2\% accuracy in detecting data quality anomalies, representing a 6.8\% relative improvement over rule-only methods. Missing value imputation using MissForest attained R² values of 0.89 for continuous variables and 92.3\% classification accuracy for categorical variables. The framework demonstrated linear scalability up to 10 million records with processing times of 3.2 minutes per million records on standard computing infrastructure.}
      \field{month}{1}
      \field{title}{A {Scalable} {Data} {Quality} {Assessment} and {Automated} {Cleaning} {Framework} for {Large}-{Scale} {Healthcare} {Databases} {Using} {Python}-{Based} {Machine} {Learning} and {Rule}-{Driven} {Validation} {Techniques}}
      \field{year}{2024}
    \endentry
